1 961

Sunday 1 January

Took Gracie to church this morning.

This morning did considerable work on Brattstrom's thesis on the Crotalidae.

Also worked on accounts, straightening out my checkbook in which I had made 3 mistakes

Am hour's talk with Allan this morning about KW affairs.

Wrote several letters

Finished reading Brattstrom's thesis and made notes for discussing with Reid Moran and others.

1 961

Monday 2 January

Spent a lot of time watching football on TV, including all

the Rose Bowl game. But still got quite a bit done. Wrote

letters and finished my comments and suggestions on

Brattstrom's paper.
----------------------------------------------------------
(January 7, continued from Jan 5)

David L. Jameson (S.D. State) told of his work with

Hyla regilla; also building up the staff at

S.D. State. He introduced Pat. Goset and Jim conley

of San Diego State Don Hunsaker of San Diego State is

working on the behavior of lizards, especially Sceloporus.

Lynett Roth and Michael H. Smith of San Diego State

spoke briefly of their work After they had all talked I was

invited to say a few words and talked (too long) on

comparisons of present and past activities, program,

collecting with Van Denburgh, Slevin,

et al, old meetings of the LA Herp. Aoc, etc. Also, (after

an interval) talked about Chapman Grant and his work

with Herpetologria.

We all went to lunch at "The Barrel" and then returned for

a view of specimans and laboratory work going on a USC.

A worthwhile trip in every way.

1 961

Tuesday 3 January

At the office this morning.

Spent a lot of time getting my savings bank books balanced

and withdrawing enough to pay off the $10,000 note at 4 1/2%

that I borrowed from the B of A last week.

Wrote the State Motor Vehicle Dept that I no longer owned the

Chev that I sold young Tussey last September. They had sent

me a registration certificate for renewal.

Returned the Brattstrom thesis to Reid Moran at the Natural

History Museum with my comments.

1 961

Wednesday 4 January

At the office this morning.

Spent most of the time today preparing for the panel show

tomorrow at the Rotary Club. Title What's Ahead for 1961.

Called on the Bogles from Tucson at Ruth Budrow's, 5 to 630.
----------------------------------------
(January 7 continued from Jan 6)

Anthony J (Tony) Gaudin (USC) is working on the

tadpoles of Hyla regilla & H Californiae.

Shelly Johnson (USC) is working on the

chuckawallas. He has tagged a number and watches them

through a 25-power spotting scope. Also making measurements

and checking gonad development.

Richard A Pimental (Cal Poly) is studying 3 faunal

areas in the vicinity of San Luis Obispo.

Dr. James A. Peters of San Fernando State College is

preparing a dictionary of herpetological terms. It has

already been accepted by a publisher. New terms or new use

of old terms. Is also working on Ecuddonean herpetology and

methods of handling clinal variations.

Dick Loomis (Long Beach State) is studying chiggers,

both those on reptiles and others. Long Beach has a fairly

large collection
(continued on Jan 5)

Notes:

Stacy

Ecuddonean herpetology?

1 961

Thursday 5 January

At the office this morning. Worked on the required material

for the Rotary meeting this noon -- a panel show in the

future of San Diego. My brief part seemed to go ok.

Stayed for a meeting of the Rotary Historical Committee;

got home at 2:45. Worked on recording Christmas cards

tonight. Talked to Dick Pourade about specialized libraries

along his line
------------------------------------------------------
(Jan. 7, continued from Jan 4)
of reptiles from the West Coast of Mexico. At the present

he is working in the Joshua Tree National Monument.

Julius C. Geest (Long Beach State) is in charge of the

collection. Kenneth D. Peyton (Long Beach State) is

also a chigger man.

Robert C. Stephens (El Camino College, Chino) is

working in Joshua Tree NM using traps.

Dr. Findley E. Russell of LA County Hospital told of

his work with snake venoms and treatment.

Bayard H. Brathstrom (Orange Co State College)

described his work forming a new department at Fullerton;

also his work in optiology of the Crotalidae. Also his work

at Adelphi
(continued in Jan 2)

1 961

Friday 6 January

At the office this morning

Talked to Allan this afternoon about KW affairs

Worked on year-end accounts.
------------------------------------------------------
(Saturday, Jan 7, continued)
study of opeological characters. He is getting fine results

by this method, which greatly extends the available

material beyond skeletons or cleaned specimens.

Priscilla (Holly) Starrelt is working on frog

categories. Arnold Kluge (USC), using soft x-rays, is

working on the osteology of lizards, particularly geckos.

He is now working on Coleonyx among others.

David B. Wake (USC) is working on salamanders,

especially Aneides. Uses cleaned and stained specimens.

Arden H Brame, Jr (USC) is working on salamanders,

particularly at the species level; including some from

Costa Rica. He is also studying the Batrachoseps

relationship between attenuatus pacificus

Jim Vial (USC) is working on the ranges and

relationships between Sceloporus orcutti an

S. Magister. Also Corta Ricanskell
(continued on Jan 4)

1 961

Saturday 7 January

Today I drove up to Los Angeles with Chuck Shaw to

attend an informal meeting of southern California

herpetologists called by Jay M. savage at USC for the

purpose of telling each other what the varous individual

are doing in order to avoid duplication or overlapping. It

proved to be a worth-while meeting

Shaw was about 35 minutes late arriving at my home but

it didn't make any particular difference as we didn't miss

anything. I drove up; he drove back. We took my 53 cad. We

started up at 7:35 and arrived at 9:50. The return was made

from 2:30 to 4:30. The weather was perfect and the traffic

not too bad, at least until we passed the old tire company

factory.

THere were about 25 herpetologists present. The meeting

started with a brief talk by Savage on the general

extent of herpetological activity in southern Calif. Then

each worker gave a summary of his present activities and

future program. It went like this:

Richard Etheridge (USC) is making extensive use of low-voltage X-Rays for the
(continued on Jan 6)

1 961

Sunday 8 January

Spent part of the morning checking up to see what I had done on the paper that I have been invited to prepare for the 50th anniversary number of Copeia on the development of North American herpetology up to 1850.

Made a start on income tax calculations today.

1 961

Thursday 19 January

At the office this morning. Had a long talk with Sherwin

about organizational matters.

Spent a lot of time today touching up the Campo story for

tonight.

Tonight went to the Annual dinner of the San Diego Historical

Society and gave the speech on "A T.V. Western Sixty Years

Ago", in other words, Campo in 1899. I think it went OK.

Took about 32 minutes. It is much easier to make a talk

when you are not rushed for time; in fact I used less time

than they said I could take. Took gg to the dinner;

Phil came later.

Talked to Stanley Williams about progress in bottle

Receivede an interesting series of newspaper clippings from

Frank Gander.

Meeting of the Zoo board tonight 5:15 to 9:15 with dinner.

1 961

Thursday 2 February

At the office this morning.

Attended a session with Hi Dillin and Hayden Ames

wherein the witnesses at the coming rate case went over

their prepared testimony.

This afternoon went with Ken Frocke of the local Air

Pollution Control organization to a meeting of the Southern

California Council at the California Hotel in San

Bernardino. Started at 3:10 and arrived at 5:15. Returned

9:30 to 12:30. The return trip was slowed up by bad fog

between Paris and Temecula. It was really tough and slow

going. Fortunately Ken is a good and careful

driver.

The meeting was a total loss. Badly conducted and confused

with everyone talking at once it wasn't worth going across

the street to attend. Nothing accomplished except for sme

resolutions asking for more state and federal assistance.

14 present.

As usual the meeting was delayed while everyone got drinks

at the bar. The steak dinner was good.

Some work on income tax today.

1 961

Saturday 4 February

Some chores and letters in the morning.

Went to the annual Stanford Conference at 12. At lunch (a

rather poor one at the Catamaran Hotel) heard a fine talk

by President Wallace Sterling.

Then in the afternoon two discussions "The Proper Education

of the Scientisit" by Leonard I Schiff, Prof. of

Physics. "The Urgent and the Essential" by

Philip R. Rhinelander, dean of Humanities and Science.

They were good but not outstanding

Perry Crawford phoned tonight.

Norris Bostwick 445 South Hobart Blvd, LA5 came around

tonight. Brought his wife, nephew and niece. He just wanted

to talk over old times. He went to University Heights

school about 1902. The other people weren't interesed and

got pretty tired and sour before the session was over and

so did I.

Notes:

Stacy

LA5?

1 961

Monday 6 February

At the office this morning. Sat in on some sessions working

with the witnesses in the forthcoming rate cases. Also from

2:30 to 4:30 this afternoon.

At noon went over to Coronado and had lunch with the Kelly's,

Lena Clark, and GG at the Coronado Hotel. It was a good lunch.

John J. Ricards returned again this afternoon and did more work on Sonora.

This afternoon Louis P Faldborg, formerly of Chula

vista phoned. He is now a handy man at State College.

He collected a lot of rattlers for me around 1924.

He had recently seen Rattlesnakes in the State

College Library and was greatly pleased to have found

himself quoted in the book.

Monday 13 March

At the office this morning.

Meeting of the Directors of the Natural History Museum this afternoon 4-5:30.

Was surprised to learn from Geo Lindsay that the U.C. Press

was offering Rattlesnakes at a special discount that

brought the cost, wholesale, down almost to $8.00 per set.

I had been told at the time of publication by Fruge that

they aimed to keep a book like this in their catalogue for

from 20 to 25 years. Now they have about 700 left and sales

have been at the rate of about 185 per year, or a 4 year

supply. I don't understand this change in policy. (see entry under March 7)

Received today from the Philatelic Agency my latest order of sheets, the largest I have ever placed.

1 961

Wednesday 15 March

At the office this morning.

Talked to Hi Dillin about gas supply matters and the meeting

of the F.P.C scheduled for April 12 in Washington.

At about 2:30 I received a call from Andrew Mills, of

True Magazine, 67 West 44th St, N.Y. 36. He wanted to know

why he hadn't received the photograph he had requested last

week from GG. I told him I wouldn't send him a photo

until I had had a chance to read the prospective article;

that I had been in too many deals wherein the proofs came

too late to permit changes. I had nothing to gain from the

publication of the article and didn't want to be

embarrassed by having something printed that was

exaggerated and lurid. I said there was already too much

exhibitionism in herpetology. He promised to send the

MS. I gave him my address. The photos are to be laboratory shots; something with a reptile involved.

1961

Wednesday 5 April

At the office this morning until 11. Then went home and got

the Pliny books out as an exhibit to go with the talk at the Wendesday Club.

Gave the Pliny talk to the Club at 1:30. It took 40

minutes, and went OK, I think. At least they seemed pleased.

According to my records the talks I have given to this club have been as follows

Book Collecting March 10, 1037

Early Days in San Diego Dec 13, 1944

The Atomic Bomb and Its Aftermath Jan 16, 1946

Is Community Population Growth Desirable? April 25, 1952

A Look at the Atom Today and Tomorrow Feb 10, 1954

Smog: Is it a Threat to San Diego? Feb 22, 1956

The Writing and Publishing of a Book Mar 13, 1957

Sputniks, Science,a nd Technology May 21 1958

Darwin After 100 Years, April 8 1959

A Delayed Book Review (Pliny) April 5 1961
(Later)
The Population Explosion May 2, 1962

Notes:

Stacy

1 961

Friday 21 April

Meeting of Library Commission 9-10:30. Then to the office.

Dick Schwenckmeyer called with his zoology class this afternoon to see my collection. Talked to them briefly.

Went to Zoo this evening to a meeting of the Biological
Research Institute.

PF Scholande talked on during animals and heart rates and anoxia.

Also there were talks on valley fever; and the effects of Peruvian altitudes on men and animals.

Had a long talk with Ray Cowles. He is exceedingly

pessimistic about conditions in Africa from which he as just

returned after 6 months in Natal; pessimistic about humans and animals as well.

1 961

Monday 8 May

At the office this morning.

Started to organize the AK biographical material.

Talked with Jameson about the proposed article on the

history of American herpetology up to 1850 for copies in

1963. Told him a decision was necessary as to whether it was

to be on herpetology or hepetologists; if the former it would

large discuss the work of Europeans; if the latter almost

exclusively Americans. Pope is to do the companion work

covering subsequent to 1850. In any case Schmidt's work

published by Cal. Acad. Sci. is not to be duplicated.

Jameson with confer with the other editor and advice.

Notes:

Stacy

1 961

Wednesday 10 May

Dr. Edward H. Taylor of U. Kansas called this morning.

On his way to a collecting trip in Borneo. Visiting a married daughter here.

Went to the office for a few minutes this morning; then to

the funeral of Mrs. Rowe, Betty Jane's aunt.

At 11:15 picked up Taylor at the Natural History Museum.

Went to lunch with Taylor and Chuck Shaw at the Zoo.

Then Shaw took us on a very educational tour of the reptile house and the childrens zoo.

After that Taylor and I took the regular bus tour.

Taylor was much impressed.

At 5 took Taylor to a hotel where he met his son-in-law.

He leaves tomorrow. He looked at a few specimens in my basement.

1 961

Friday 12 May

Philip picked me up at 7:35 this morning and we boarded

a bus at Lindberg Field for a tour of S.D.G+E, Southern Counties gas Co, and

El Paso Natural gas co gas transmission facilities.

We started at about 8.

went out US 395. The first stop was at our Moreno Compressor Station.

On the way out W.C. Prill, Educational Services Manager,

and J.A. Miller, Vice President-Transmission and Supply,

Southern Counties, explained many features of the systems,

and natural gas supply problems as well as describing the

pipeline network. This was all very well done; for clarity

and interest. Zitlau of our company also talked. Sat with Philip

From Moreno we went via highway to the Southern Counties Indio station.

Here we had a fine buffet lunch in the Southern Counties garage.

Also a few brief talks illustrated with maps and charts.

We then proceeded to the turbine compressor station at Desert Center.

Enroute it was quite windy; the dust was thick; also some rain

Reached the Desert Inn Motel at Blythe at about 5.

Rested for a while. Here we got news of the Public

Utilities Commission to give us any interim relief.

Met Hi Dillin here; suggested he talk to Louis Knerr.

(Continued on May 11)

Notes:

Stacy

1 961

Saturday 13 May

This morning we left the motel at 8 and had a ranch breakfast

around the Southern Counties pool at the compressor station.

We then went to Ehrenberg, Arizona, and inspected the gas

line crossing over the Colorado River.

A brief talk by H.F. Steen, VP and Mgr. of Pipe Line Operations;

also a very humorous talk, filled by Texas stories, by one of the El Paso men.

The rest of the party returned to San Diego by air, but

I drove back with the Dillins, stopping for lunch at Indio.

We started at 10:30 and got home at 3:50.

We went over the hill via the Palms to Pines highway and Anza.

Spent the afternoon and evening catching up.

1 961

Friday 19 May

Arrived in San Francisco at 8:30. Went up to the

Fairmont and read until 9:45; then went across the

street to the Mark Hopkins. It was raining; I had neither

rain coat nor umbrella.

Attended a meeting of the Board of Directors of the

California State Chamber of Commerce from 10 to 1:35.

The LA members traveling by air were delayed because of the weather.

Had an indifferent lunch and then took a taxi to the East Bay Terminal; didn't wait for the speeches.

Got the the Bancroft Library at U.C. at 2:40 and drew

out a form of the Volcano and Jackson, Amador County,

Ledger. Vol 1, no 1 was published Oct. 27, 1855. The last

number was dated Jan 9, 1858. By that time the paper had

moved from Volcano to Jackson. I found a number of ads for

my father's business. It was called

The Sacromento Store, A. Klauber and Co. The

owner's names were given up in the corners as

A. Klauber, Volcano and F Mandelbaum,

Sacramento. The ads contained summaries of goods

handled. The Library had only one
(Continued on May 17)

Thursday 25 May

Thursday 25 May

At the office this morning.

Some work on the AK biography.

This afternoon went to a meeting of the Southern California Air Pollution Coordinating Council.

Drove up with Supervisor Gisbson; others along were Askew and

Flocke. Left at 3:30 and arrived at 5. The meeting was

at the Greenbrier Inn at Garden Grove. The gang stood

around the bar until 7:15; and unfortunate delay for those

of us who had to drive a long distance.

1 961

Friday 21 July

Went to the zoo this morning to get my mail that

Chuck Shaw had promised to deliver but failed.

Then to the office. Discussed the rate-case briefs with

Hi Dillin; also smog with Dillin and Noble.

Wrote letters this afternoon. Then to a meeting of the

Southern California Air Pollution Coordinating Council at the King's Inn, Mission Valley, from 3 to 5:30.

The meeting was better conducted and more interesting than the usual run. At least they had an agenda.

Ducked the smog dinner and went to the dinner meeting of the

Biological Research Institute at the Zoo.

Talks on the use of radioactive isotopes to determine the life span of red blood cells in mammals.

Also on the metabolism of alligators.

This lasted from 7 to 9:30. Then got some specimens from Shaw.

Got home at 10. A long tiring day.

Dr. Gordon Ball asked after Donnie.

1 961

Wednesday 26 July

At the office this morning. Spent a lot of time studying the

Zoo's operating budget for 1961-1962

Received a call from Elizabeth Kerby, 444 14th St,

Santa Monica, a free-lance writer. She is contemplating

an article for Life, which, if I understood her correctly,

will deal with the work of amateur zoologists. (But this has been done before).

Talked with her for 30 minutes by phone. Gave her plenty of information but I question whether she could get it down.

Promised to send her a Rattlesnake brochure.

Her proposed article would appear in December.

Meeting of the Economic Research Bureau of the Chamber of Commerce 3 -5 this afternoon.

Meeting of the Zoo Finance Committee and then the Trustees from 5:15 to 8:45.

From my standpoint a very unsatisfactory decision and a

completely disconcerting discussion of the Zoo's operating budget from 1961-62.

1961

Thursday 10 August

At the office this morning.

Short conference with Mrs Beckham on some of her land problems.

Today finished the writeup of the home at 233 W. Juniper St.

Attended a meeting of the Industrial Committee of the State Chamber of Commerce from 2:15 - 3:30.

Went to La Jolla Playhouse tonight. "Invitation to a March".

A complete bust. Trying to be shocking; also moralizing with fictitious deep stuff that was plain garage.

Marge Champion was a small dividend.

Heard from Mrs. Hoover at the zoo that sales of

Rattlesnakes during the first 6 months of 1961

totalled 186 sets. There is now a credit balance in the

account of $659.38. In other words, the zoo has had its investment returned and has made a small profit.

According to my figures the UC Press still has about 440 sets available for sale.

Sunday 1 3 August

Sunday 13 August

Made some progress on the possessions and effects project. Wrote up several items.

----------------------------------------------
(August 30, continued)
were stimulated this recent half year by a general mark-down and sale that the Press had had.

Many other books besides Rattlesnakes were marked down for a while.

They evidently still deviate to some extent from the standard price of $22.50 less 40%.

We talked over the second printing. They wouldn't make up their minds yet,

but Lilienthal seemed rather sure they would embark on a

second printing when they were down to a one year's supply.

He thought the second printing should include a sort of

supplement of additional material (10-20 pages?) to come

after the index, so as not to require any change in the

present pagination. I suggested a bibliography of new items with annotations, and this seemed to meet with his approval.

He thought I should consider all these matters (continued on Aug 14)

Wednesday 16 August

Ordered, and got next day, 35 mm films of the Amador Ledger for Oct. 27, 1855 and Dec. 6, 1856.

Returning to the Territorial Enterprise, it is said that the issues published at Genoa from Dec.

In the main library I got 2 good obituaries from the SF Chronicle; Jacob Spiegl, April 12, 1909; and Louise Mandlebaum, Nov. 5, 1912.

1961

Saturday 19 August

Small progress in odds and ends today. Some letters.

Called on Janet, who has been ill.

14 guests at home tonight: Whitneys, Leighs, Austins, Grays, plus some odd females.

---------------------------------------------
(Sept. 1, continued)
mansion. First had cocktails in the garden where it was cool and pleasant.

Then adjourned indoors for a good dinner that was well served, but it was uncomfortably warm.

I sat between Yoak the chancellor of U.C. at San Diego

and Hal Champion the director of state finances. We were

all introduced individually. The speeches were short and simple.

Mrs Brown, the only woman present, was a charming, unpretentious hostess.

Got home at 9:30.

1 961

Monday 28 August

Went to the annual meeting of the Solar stockholders. Quite perfunctory as IH holds about 99% of the stock. There were no strangers present. This lasted from 9 to 9:30

Then to a meeting of the Solar board of directors. They reorganized with the same officers.

I was presented (unexpectedly) with a 15 year pin. My acceptance was badly phrased.

I left at 11:30; the meeting was not quite ended.

Went to the gas co office for the mail.

Finally got started for the north at 1:10 having done all possible packing yesterday.

Had an uneventful trip. The Freeway through Los Angeles

was fairly congested in spots, but not too bad.

It was quite warm through the San Fernando Valley.

Went via US 101 all the way.

Stopped at Los Padres Motel, 1575 Monterey St., San Luis Obispo. Arrived at 8:05. Miles today 326.

1 961

Tuesday 29 August

Left San Luis Obispo at 9:15. It was comfortably cool all day.

There is still a lot of 2-lane highway around King City, and this slows up the traffic considerably, as there are always trucks that can't be passed.

Had a rather poor lunch at Gilroy.

Stopped at Stanford Village and delivered some packages to Silvia.

Had a hard time finding the place. Melville was at the university. The kids were cute but she has a very crowded menage.

Called the Silva Motel from south San Francsico; lucky

we did so as we got the last suitable accomodation,

not too good at that -- a double bed and a cot.

Arrived at Silva's (Berkeley) at 4:30.

It was very crowded on the freeway ahead of the bridge and on the bridge. I almost got clipped once; my fault. Miles today 254.

Took Olga Epstein to dinner at the Black Sheep, which was very good.

Then adjournned to her apartment where I got some additional material for my family tree studies.

1 961

Wednesday 30 August

Called Dorie and made a date for lunch and a visit to the cemetery Sunday.

Had a very full day today, with some good luck and some bad.

First called Lilienthal at the U.C. Press and made a date to meet him at 10:30.
Frunge was out of town. Had a discussion for nearly an hour as to the future of Rattlesnakes.

He said they had tentative plans for a second printing but would not make a definite decision until they were down to about one year's supply

(=+/- 200) which he thought would be about a year from now.

He confirmed the following figures: July 1, 1960 to June 30, 1961, 94+186=280.

The July, 1961, sales were 45. He thought they had been considerably stimulated by the article in True.

There are now 467 sets left (after the July, 1961 sales).

This is slightly higher than my previous figures. Lilienthal called in his sales manager,

who discussed past sales and future possibilities. He thought they should have a new brochure.

I suggested a new mailing, especially to medical libraries and hospitals. Sales

(continued on August 13)

1 961

Thursday 31 August

GG drove me up to the postoffice where we got one large bundle of mail.

Called the Town House Motel in SF for Saturday reservations. Nothing doing; this is disquieting.

Tried to learn the whereabouts of Raymond Shapro through his former employer, Crocker Anglo Bank, but no luck.

Got to the U.C. Bancroft library at 9:50 and went to work

on the Territorial Enterprise between 1867 and 1869. It was then published in Virginia city (called Virginia).

I concentrated on April 1, 1869 to June 30, 1869,

but I found nothing of interest. There were no Genoa ads, and, in fact, no mention of Genoa.

As far as I can see there is no use in giving further consideration to the Territorial Enterprise.

Went out for a hamburger and then came back to the main UC card catalog.

I got the call numbers for a lot of items on my list, but I only ran down 4, as by 4:15

I was so tired I gave up and returned to Silva Motel.

At about 6:30 GG and I went

1 961

Saturday 2 September

This morning went to the Sacramento Host Breakfast.

Despite the fact that it was scheduled for 7:45, and

I was there a few minutes before the deadline, everyone was eating when I arrived.

The introduction of the guests (which did not include Sacramento people) took from 8:10 to 8:43, a dreary procedure.

It is astonishing that so many people come so far just to be able to stand and be introduced before this crowd.

The head table introductions took from 8:44 to 8:47.

The talks were: Wren, President of the California State Fair on their new plant; 8:54-9:02;

Bob Hornby (president of State Chamber, on political representation and the continued unification of the northern and southern halves of the state, 9:05-9:27;

1 961

Sunday 3 September

Hung around the room in the morning. The weather was quite warm.

Then went to Dorie's and had a fine lunch. Then to the DeYoung Museum where we dropped Mom,

and thence Dorie and I went to the Home of Peace Cemetery

where I made records of all the tombstone entries of Epstein, Mandlebaum, and Speigl.

Had quite a time finding the latter. Got a lot of useful dates and other items, particularly from marble tombstones,

on which they were accustomed to make quite complete entries.

But granite is too hard and the more recent entries are very brief--only the year for dates.

The only Klauber tomb was poor little Clara: died June 4, 1868.

I felt very sad to see it (She was born Feb. 22 1867).

Tonight I felt quite bad--slight fever and indigestion. Could sleep well.

1 961

Monday 4 September

This morning I felt so bad we cancelled our luncheon date with the Henckendorffs and packed for departure to Palo Alto.

Before leaving I finally reached Marie (Mrs. Raymond Shapro) the daughter of Laura Litt,

who is the last survivor of the 7 Spiegl girls.

Laura has had two strokes, is clear in her head but can't talk.

Marie spends much time at the hospital, which is why I wasn't able to reach her.

She seems to know all the other Spiegl cousins and expressed great interest in my genealogical project.

I told her I was especially anxious to get data on my grandmother Elizabeth Hahn Klauber.

I told Marie of my good forture in getting data at Bancroft on Jacob Spiegl.

I also called Mrs Carroll who is leaving for New York tomorrow. I told her of my discussion of a

possible supplement with Lichenthal. She said that the scheme for a supplement had already been used in an

Arizona botany. She said she hoped I still had the origianl photos

Thursday 7 September

Called at the Palo Alto post office for the last mail. Got one package. Left forwarding address.

It was rather warm in the San Fernando Valley.

We made only three stops: Had a buffet lunch at the Paso Robles Hotel which was quite good; gas at Santa Maria;

and canned goods and peanut brittle at Andersens at Buellton.

Got caught in a couple of bumper-to-bumper slow downs on the Hollywood Freeway despite the fact that we didn't hit it until after 6.

We ran into the De Mar race track crowd from Capistrano on; it was dark and the headlights were very annoying.

Friday 20 October

Arrived on time. Went to the St. Francis and sat around reading until time for the meeting of the Board of Directors of the California State Chamber of Commerce, which lasted from 10 until almost 12. I had no notes so my talk was rather uncoordinated and I omitted many good points. Nevertheless I talked for 35 minutes including a question period and their attention indicated a continued interest.

Wells Kelly's "First Directory of Nevada Territory" of which I had never heard until ten days ago when I saw an ad for a reprint. 1 961

Monday 30 October

At the office part of the time this morning. Went out to La Jolla on a wild-goose chase connected withe the Library. I was confused in the date.

Took my car in to Fred's place at 301 16th and had the dent made a couple of days ago by Joe Chiddi straightened.

1 961

Tuesday 31 October

At the office part of the morning. Had a talk with Ollie Owen about a right-of-way problem at Encinitas. Also a long conference with Hi Dillin about the regulation of gas producers. Also about Company legal counsel.

At 11 went up to the Zoo and had lunch with Robt Inger of Chicago and Chuck Shaw. Discussed the proposed historical article for the 1963 anniversary numbers of Copeia.

1961

Wednesday 1 November

At the office this morning until about 11. Left Cad at Tussey's account of starting trouble.

Left for Los Angeles at 1:20 and arrived at the Parkway Motel at 3:50. Congestion rather bad on the freeway close in. Got a good double room. Tonight had dinner at Carls and then went to a performance of Boris Godunov at the Shrine that lasted from 8 to 11:50. It was very enjoyable. It was in English but not much more understandable than if it had been in Russian or Italian. We were in the second row. The cast
Shuysky Herbert Handt
Boris Giorgio Tozzi
Girgori Albert Lance
Marina Irene Dalis
Rangoni Plinio Clabassi

Notes:

Stacy

Unsure about the spelling of names in the performance

Page Edit History:
  • Stacy 02/04/2013 02:22 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:04 PM

1 961

Thursday 2 November

Drove down from Los Angeles this morning 9:30-11:50. Freeway not too badly crowded. I drove the Chev. from Encinitas; first time I have driven it.

Slept part of the afternoon.

Cad still laid up.

Went to an Opera Guild dinner at the El Cortez. The usual show-off of glad rags.

Went to a performance of Lucia at the Fox. A fine show of the old fashioned romantic type of opera.

Lucia Joan Sutherland
Henry Ashton Vladimir Ruzdak
Edgardo Renato Cioni
Sutherland received great acclaim

Opera took 8:30-11:50. Full house. We had our usual front-row seats.

Wednesday 29 November

1 961

Thursday 30 November

At the office this morning.

Had a conference with Hi Dillin reference to the company's reply to an inquiry from the Public Utilities Commission regarding the Company's position on regulation of natural gas producers.

Went home about 11. Askeur and Flocke called for me at 11:50 and we went to Riverside. Stopped at a hamburger joint for a bite of lunch. Then to the Dunes for a meeting of the Southern California Air Pollution Control Council which started at 3:20 and ended at 6:30. It was fairly interesting. A Ford man discussed crank-case, blow by devices and also the suppression of tail pipe emmissions. Had an offer of a ride with Maga, but as Al Bush was going in without waiting for dinner, I went with him. Got to the Biltmore in LA at about 7:40. A fast trip. Had supper at the coffee shop and turned in. Catching a cold.

Page Edit History:

Went shopping and caught the 5:45 for San Diego. Got home at 9. A lot of sniffling.
